node.text: Over the past decade, @marthastewart48 has planted hundreds of Japanese maples on her farm in Bedford—and every autumn, the still-diminutive trees put on a dazzling show. "I first became enamored with Japanese maples when I visited Japan with my then-husband and daughter years ago. On our travels from city to countryside, we saw many types of this graceful tree. It was autumn, and their colors ranged from brilliant reds to bright oranges to yellow-golds, and even the darkest magentas. I was entranced. I vowed that I would plant as many as I could, in as many different sizes, forms, and colors as possible," writes Martha in our October issue. Feast your eyes on their brilliant foliage, and learn how she helps them thrive in our October issue out on newsstands or at the link in bio. 📷: @minh_ngoc

node.text: If you're intrigued by the speckled borlotti beans at the farmers' market, this minestrone is the perfect excuse to grab a few pounds. The hearty soup is flexible by nature—think of the ingredients as mere suggestions. Didn't find borlottis? Use butter beans instead, or canned versions of either. No escarole or kale in sight? Toss in another leafy green—say, mustard greens or chard. Last, stir in cooked pasta; any shape you can eat with a spoon will do! Get the recipe at the link in bio! 📷: @pissinginthepunchbowl recipe by: @lucullanfoods food styling by: @rebeccajurkevich prop styling by: @tanyagraff1

node.text: This bold medley combines brick chicken and sweet-and-sour agrodolce sauce in a single roasting pan. Weighing down the chicken with a skillet while you sear it ensures a crispy, golden skin for this brick chicken. Then you sauté a mess of peppers, any mix works for this dish, with onion and garlic, mix in vinegar, sugar, and capers, and combine it all with the browned bird, so the flavors meld as it finishes cooking in the oven. Get the recipe at the link in bio! 📷: @pissinginthepunchbowl recipe by: @lucullanfoods food styling by: @rebeccajurkevich prop styling by: @tanyagraff1

node.text: This ode to a classic Greek galatopita, or milk pie, will knock the socks off your friends who order pumpkin-spice everything. Martha's ruffled pumpkin milk pie is also the ideal exposure therapy if you're new to baking with phyllo. You simply brush sheets of it with clarified butter, scrunch them into accordion-like shapes, and arrange them in a spiral in the pan. Once you've got your phyllo base, blind-bake it to crisp up the top, then pour a cardamom-infused pumpkin-purée custard over it and bake it again to set. Check out more recipes from @marthastewart48’s upcoming book Fruit Desserts: 100+ Ways to Savor the Best of Every Season at the link in bio. 📷: @johnny_miller_ recipe by: @laurarege

node.text: After Labor Day comes and goes, there's an exciting back to school, back to business spirit in the air, but we think it's also important to take some time to embrace the actual change in seasons. To help you welcome the arrival of fall, we're turning to @marthastewart48 for all of our autumnal inspiration. From spooky halloween decor to show-stopping turkey-inspired treats (that guests will rave about for years to come!), photos from Martha's own properties show us how to revel in fall's glory. Visit the link in bio to learn more! 👆🏼
